es is set to premiere on April 15, 2020.<ref name=\"SeriesPremiereDate\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/fx-sets-premiere-dates-for-fargo-mrs-america-better-things-devs-archer-more-tca-1202825595/|title=FX Sets Premiere Dates For 'Fargo', 'Mrs. America', 'Better Things', 'Devs', 'Archer' & More \u2013 TCA|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|location=Los Angeles, California|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=January 9, 2020|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAlongside the series order, [[Cate Blanchett]] was announced to star.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/> In May 2019, [[Uzo Aduba]], [[Rose Byrne]], [[Kayli Carter]], [[Ari Graynor]], [[Melanie Lynskey]], [[James Marsden]], [[Margo Martindale]], [[Sarah Paulson]], [[John Slattery]], [[Jeanne Tripplehorn]] and [[Tracey Ullman]] were added to the series.<ref name=\"cast 1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/uzo-aduba-james-marsden-sarah-paulson-rose-byrne-cate-blanchett-fx-mrs-america-1202614271/|title=Uzo Aduba, James Marsden, Sarah Paulson, More Join Cate Blanchett in FX's 'Mrs. America'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|location=Los Angeles, California|first=Anita|last=Bennett|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, [[Elizabeth Banks]] was cast to star while Bria Henderson was set to recur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/elizabeth-banks-cast-mrs-america-fx-limited-series-1202626918/|title=Elizabeth Banks To Co-Star in FX Limited Series 'Mrs. America'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|location=Los Angeles, California|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/p-valley-casts-thomas-q-jones-bria-henderson-joins-mrs-america-1202637912/|title='P-Valley' Casts Thomas Q. Jones; Bria Henderson Joins 'Mrs. America'|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=June 25, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|location=Los Angeles, California|access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> [[Niecy Nash]] was cast in a recurring role in August, with Olivia Scriven cast in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/mrs-america-niecy-nash-recur-fx-limited-series-1202669559/|title='Mrs. America': Niecy Nash To Recur in FX Limited Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=August 16, 2019|accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/mrs-america-olivia-scriven-recur-fx-limited-series-cate-blanchett-1202766260/|title='Mrs. America': Olivia Scriven To Recur in FX Limited Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for the series took place from June 19 to November 1, 2019 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Current Productions {{!}} IATSE 873 |url=https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions|website=IATSE 873|accessdate=October 23, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023164713/https://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions|archivedate=October 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe first three episodes were premiered on [[Hulu]] under '' FX on Hulu'' label on April 15, 2020. In [[India]] the series started streaming on Hulu and FX's corporate sibling [[Disney+ Hotstar]] on April 16, 2020<ref name=\"Firstpost 2020\">{{cite web | title=Mrs. America review: Cate Blanchett and the anti-feminist mystique of FX-Hulu\u2019s ERA-defining drama- Entertainment News, Firstpost | website=Firstpost | date=April 16, 2020 | url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/mrs-america-review-cate-blanchett-and-the-anti-feminist-mystique-of-fx-hulus-era-defining-drama-8266671.html | access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Reception==\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the miniseries holds an approval rating of 95% based on 58 reviews, with an average rating of 8.22/10. The website's critical consensus states, \"''Mrs. America'' captures the complicated life and times of Phyllis Schlafly with poise and style to spare, brought to vividlife by a superb ensemble led by another masterful performance from Cate Blanchett.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/mrs_america/s01|title=Mrs. America: Season 1 (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 87 out of 100 based on 35 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/mrs-america/season-1|title=Mrs. America: Season 1|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.fxnetworks.com/shows/mrs-america}}\n* {{IMDb title|9244556}}\n\n{{Hulu}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s American drama television miniseries]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:FX Networks original programming]]\n[[Category:Hulu original programming]]\n", "name_user": "Afrayednot", "label": "safe", "comment": "<ref>https://www.fxnetworks.com/shows/mrs-america/cast-crew</ref>", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mrs._America_(miniseries)"}
{"title_page": "Chi\u0219in\u0103u Independence Day Parade", "text_new": "{{Short description|National event in Chisinau, Moldova}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name=Chisinau Independence Day Parade\n|image=File:08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 04.jpg\n|image_size=\n|caption=The parade in 2016.\n|native_name=Parada Militar\u0103 a Chi\u0219in\u0103u de Ziua Independen\u021bei Republicii Moldova  \n|native_name_lang=\n|country={{flag|Moldova}}\n|date=August 27\n|begins=10:30 am\n|ends=12:00 pm\n|prev=2016\n|next=2021 (expected)\n|frequency=Quinquennial\n|location=[[Chisinau]]\n|first=\n|genre=[[Military parades]]\n|organised=\n|website=\n|venue=[[Great National Assembly Square, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Great National Assembly Square]]\n}}\nThe '''Chi\u0219in\u0103u Independence Day Parade''' is one of the events of the [[Independence Day (Moldova)|Independence Day of Moldova]] held by the [[Moldovan National Army]]. The parade is held in [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], [[Moldova]] on August 27 every 5 to 10 years on [[Great National Assembly Square, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Great National Assembly Square]].\n\n==History of Moldovan military parades==\n[[File:08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 03.jpg|thumb|The [[22nd Peacekeeping Battalion (Moldova)|22nd Peacekeeping Battalion]] during the parade.]]\nBefore 1991 parades in the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]] were held in honor of the [[October Revolution]], [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]], and until 1969 [[International Workers' Day|May Day]]. In 1976, Chisinau hosted a parade in honor of the 50th anniversary of its integration into the [[Soviet Union]], held in the presence of General Secretary [[Leonid Brezhnev]] and First Secretary [[Ivan Bodiul]].<ref>https://ru.sputnik.md/photo/20181009/22210371/brejnev-moldova-chisinau-mssr.html</ref> The final military parade in the Moldovan SSR took place in 1989 in honor of the [[October Revolution]], which was marred by [[1989 Moldova civil unrest|protests that occurred in the capital]]. On the morning of 7 November, a group of 100 people from the [[Popular Front of Moldova]] took candles and stood in front of Soviet tanks preparing for the parade. As a result, the mobile column of the parade was interrupted and abruptly canceled by the ruling authorities, with the leaders of [[Communist Party of Moldova]] left the central stage immediately.<ref>https://ru.sputnik.md/amp/analytics/20160904/8846533/moldova-ussr-narod-prazdniki.html</ref><ref>file:///C:/Users/glaws_000/Downloads/Musteata%20Euxeinos%2015%2016_2014.pdf</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1989/11/07/Soviet-Revolution-Day-celebrations-disrupted/1102626418000/|title=Soviet Revolution Day celebrations disrupted|access-date=2017-02-11|language=en|newspaper=UPI}}</ref> Moldova would never hold another military parade until 2001.\n\n==Independence parades==\nThe following parades were held in recent years:\n\n* In 2001, Moldova celebrated the 10th anniversary of independence. It was the first parade since the fall of the USSR and was ordered by President [[Vladimir Voronin]] in early July.<ref>https://www.legis.md/cautare/getResults?doc_id=57381&lang=ro</ref><ref>http://lex.justice.md/index.php?action=view&view=additional&id=287992&lang=1</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Moldova+Independence+Day|title=On August 27, 2001, the first military parade was held in Chisinau to celebrate the first 10 years of the country's independence.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l4BpAAAAMAAJ&q=Moldova+independence+day+parade.&dq=Moldova+independence+day+parade.&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiL_oWE9Z_cAhUY24MKHYJEAy0Q6AEIOjAG|title=Russia & Eurasia Facts & Figures Annual|date=19 August 2018|publisher=Academic International Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* 2011 celebrated the 20th anniversary of independence.<ref>https://www.dw.com/ro/moldova-%C3%AEn-pas-european-de-defilare-la-20-de-ani-de-independen%C5%A3%C4%83/a-15345526</ref> Acting President [[Marian Lupu]], who signed the order for the parade that April<ref>http://ru.interlic.md/2011-04-20/v-kishineve-po-sluchaju-20j-godovcshiny-provozglashenija-nezavisimosti-moldovy-projdet-voennyj-parad-20794.html</ref> delivered the holiday address during the parade. Inspecting the parade was the [[Ministry of Defense (Moldova)|Minister of Defense]] of Moldova [[Vitalie Marinu\u021ba]] while the officer commanding the parade was Brigadier General Vitalie Stoian from the National Army's General Staff.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=835#.WaWth8tOkwg]</ref> Dress rehearsals took place three, seven and ten days before the parade, with the first rehearsal on August being attended by [[Prime Minister of Moldova]] [[Vlad Filat]].<ref>https://regnum.ru/news/1436300.html</ref><ref>https://www.blackseanews.net/read/23266</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/index.php?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=825#.WaN9vctOkwg|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=814#.WaN9wctOkwg|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|accessdate=2017-08-28}}</ref> It was the first time [[military equipment]] had been brought to the central square sine 1989.<ref>http://www.vedomosti.md/news/Moldova_Prazdnuet_20yu_Godovshchinu_Provozglasheniya_Nezavisimosti</ref> At the head of the parade were the [[flag of Moldova]], as well as the military banners of the Emperor [[Stefan the Great]], which were brought to Chisinau from [[Romania]] as a gesture on their part.<ref>https://point.md/ru/novosti/obschestvo/vladimir-filat-skoro-kazhdij-politicheskij-lider-kazhdij-deputat-kazhdaya-partiya-dolzhni-budut-prodemonstrirovatj-politicheskuyu-zrel</ref> The contingent of veterans of the [[Transnistrian War]] was led by [[Division General]] [[Ion Costa\u0219]], a former [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Moldova)|Minister of Interior]] (1990\u20131992) and Defence (1992).<ref name=\":11\">https://gagauzinfo.md/top1/1389-v-kishineve-proshel-voennyjj-parad-po.html</ref> A new, more western style marching formula was used for the parade<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=699#.WgiVCWOnHEZ|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-11-12}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> as well as new military uniforms were used during the parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=729#.WaN9O8tOkwg|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-08-28}}</ref>\n* 2016 celebrated the [[silver jubilee]] of Moldovan independence. It was the first to use a revised format that was similar to the [[Great Union Day]] Parade in [[Bucharest]]. The following 6 foreign contingents took part in the parade for the first time: [[Odessa Military Academy]] ([[Ukraine]]),{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} the [[Michael the Brave 30th Guards Brigade]] and the [[Asociatia Traditia Militara]] contingent ([[Romania]]), the [[Representative Honor Guard Battalion of the Polish Armed Forces]] ([[Poland]]), the [[Grand Duke Gediminas Staff Battalion]] ([[Lithuania]]), and a 4-man group from the [[Royal Irish Regiment (1992)|Royal Irish Regiment]] ([[United Kingdom]]).{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} Servicemen of the [[Russian Armed Forces]] were also invited to the parade.<ref>https://novostipmr.com/ru/news/16-07-19/rossiyskie-voennye-priglasheny-na-parad-v-chest-25-letiya</ref> More than 2,000 soldiers, as well as veterans of the army marched in the parade. The commander of the parade was the [[Chief of the General Staff (Moldova)|Chief of the General Staff of the Moldovan Armed Forces]], Brigadier General Igor Cutie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=3976#.WaNz-MtOkwj|title=The military parade was opened by Parade\u2019s Commander, Brigadier Gen. Igor Cutie, owner of \"Credinta Patriei\" order, holder of \"Meritul Militar\" medal, and participant to the war for the independence and territorial integrity of the Republic of Moldova,}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.kp.md/online/news/2493337/|title=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435 [\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e+\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e]|last=\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|first=\u0422\u041a\u0410\u0427 \u041b\u0438\u0434\u0438\u044f {{!}} \u0421\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439|date=2016-08-28|work=KP.MD - \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|access-date=2017-11-11}}</ref> During the 2016 parade, Moldovan police fired tear gas to disperse anti-government protesters who were participating in the [[2015\u201316 protests in Moldova|2015\u201316 protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/08/27/protests-tear-gas-at-moldova-independence-day-parade.html|title=Protests, tear gas at Moldova independence day parade|date=2016-08-27|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-07-03|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Moldovan Police Clash With Protesters On Independence Day|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/moldova-independence-day/27950971.html|accessdate=2017-07-03}}</ref> Opposition parties previously had called for rallies to disrupt the military parade, launching an \"I'm not afraid\" campaign on social media. Opposition lawyer Anna Ursaki said the following in favor of protests: \"If the authorities have the right to organize parades, to have a feast during the plague, when people are miserable, we have the right to protests\".<ref>https://novostipmr.com/ru/news/16-08-22/v-moldove-oppoziciya-prizvala-mitingami-sorvat-parad-v-chest</ref>\n\n==Parade composition==\nThe parade has the following general composition:<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>https://ria.ru/20110827/423854478.html</ref>\n\n*Officers of the National Army\n*[[Honor Guard Company (Moldova)|Honor Guard Company]]\n*Infantry Troops\n*[[22nd Peacekeeping Battalion (Moldova)|22nd Peacekeeping Battalion]]\n*Paratroopers\n*[[Moldovan Border Police]]\n*Officers of the Ministry of the Interior\n*\u0218tefan cel Mare Police Academy\n*Lyceum of police\n*Special-purpose brigade\n*[[State Protection and Guard Service of Moldova]]\n*Civil Protection and Emergency Situations Service\n*[[Trupele de Carabinieri]]\n*[[Alexandru cel Bun Military Academy]]\n\n===Military bands in attendance===\n[[File:Orchestra preziden\u021bial\u0103.jpeg|thumb|The [[Presidential Orchestra of the Republic of Moldova]]]]\nThe [[military band]]s of the Chisinau Garrison who take part in the parade are composed of:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.publika.md/parada-militara-impresionanta-de-ziua-independentei-moldovei-cine-va-participa-in-premiera_2724211.html|title=Military parade dedicated to the anniversary of 25 years since Moldova's independence will end with the evolution of the orchestra mixed garrison Chisinau, composed of five military orchestras: Presidential Orchestra of the Republic of Moldova, Orchestra Brigade 1st Infantry Motorized \"Moldova\" Balti Orchestra Brigade two motorized infantry \"\u015etefan cel Mare\" in Chisinau Orchestra Motorized Brigade 3rd Infantry \"Dacia\" Cahul Orchestra model Carabineer Troops Department of the Interior Ministry, MIA Border Police Band.|access-date=}}</ref>\n \n* The [[Presidential Orchestra of the Republic of Moldova]]\n* The Band of the [[1st Motorized Infantry Brigade \"Moldova\"|1st Motorized Infantry Brigade]]\n* The Band of the [[2nd Motorized Infantry Brigade \"Stefan Cel Mare\"|2nd Motorized Infantry Brigade]]\n* The Band of the [[3rd Motorized Infantry Brigade \"Dacia\"|3rd Motorized Infantry Brigade]]\n* [[Band of the Department of Carabinier Troops]]\n* [[Central Band of the Moldovan Border Police|Central Band of the Border Police]]\n\n== Photos of the parade ==\n<gallery>\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 08.jpg|\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 07.jpg|\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 10.jpg|\nFile:08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 06.jpg|Ukrainian troops drawn from the [[Odessa Military Academy]] during the 2016 parade.\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 06.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kiev Independence Day Parade]]\n* [[Minsk Independence Day Parade]]\n\n== Videos ==\n* [https://m.youtube.com/watch?list=PL030PgM6el9I_ftCCk-fIW8w407R1slAo&v=ga7mFVlWRag 2001 Chisinau Independence Day Parade.]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4LZAOiNTdUg 2011 Chisinau Independence Day Parade.]\n* [https://m.youtube.com/watch?list=PL030PgM6el9I_ftCCk-fIW8w407R1slAo&params=OAFIAVgB&v=8RphgV0ubiY&mode=NORMAL 2016 Chisinau Independence Day Parade.]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chi\u0219in\u0103u Independence Day Parade}}\n[[Category:Military parades]]\n[[Category:Events in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]\n[[Category:Summer events in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Military of Moldova]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|National event in Chisinau, Moldova}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name=Chisinau Independence Day Parade\n|image=File:08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 04.jpg\n|image_size=\n|caption=The parade in 2016.\n|native_name=Parada Militar\u0103 a Chi\u0219in\u0103u de Ziua Independen\u021bei Republicii Moldova  \n|native_name_lang=\n|country={{flag|Moldova}}\n|date=August 27\n|begins=10:30 am\n|ends=12:00 pm\n|prev=2016\n|next=2021 (expected)\n|frequency=Quinquennial\n|location=[[Chisinau]]\n|first=\n|genre=[[Military parades]]\n|organised=\n|website=\n|venue=[[Great National Assembly Square, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Great National Assembly Square]]\n}}\nThe '''Chi\u0219in\u0103u Independence Day Parade''' is one of the events of the [[Independence Day (Moldova)|Independence Day of Moldova]] held by the [[Moldovan National Army]]. The parade is held in [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], [[Moldova]] on August 27 every 5 to 10 years on [[Great National Assembly Square, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Great National Assembly Square]].\n\n==History of Moldovan military parades==\n[[File:08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 03.jpg|thumb|The [[22nd Peacekeeping Battalion (Moldova)|22nd Peacekeeping Battalion]] during the parade.]]\nBefore 1991 parades in the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]] were held in honor of the [[October Revolution]], [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]], and until 1969 [[International Workers' Day|May Day]]. In 1976, Chisinau hosted a parade in honor of the 50th anniversary of its integration into the [[Soviet Union]], held in the presence of General Secretary [[Leonid Brezhnev]] and First Secretary [[Ivan Bodiul]].<ref>https://ru.sputnik.md/photo/20181009/22210371/brejnev-moldova-chisinau-mssr.html</ref> The final military parade in the Moldovan SSR took place in 1989 in honor of the [[October Revolution]], which was marred by [[1989 Moldova civil unrest|protests that occurred in the capital]]. On the morning of 7 November, a group of 100 people from the [[Popular Front of Moldova]] took candles and stood in front of Soviet tanks preparing for the parade. As a result, the mobile column of the parade was interrupted and abruptly canceled by the ruling authorities, with the leaders of [[Communist Party of Moldova]] left the central stage immediately.<ref>https://ru.sputnik.md/amp/analytics/20160904/8846533/moldova-ussr-narod-prazdniki.html</ref><ref>file:///C:/Users/glaws_000/Downloads/Musteata%20Euxeinos%2015%2016_2014.pdf</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1989/11/07/Soviet-Revolution-Day-celebrations-disrupted/1102626418000/|title=Soviet Revolution Day celebrations disrupted|access-date=2017-02-11|language=en|newspaper=UPI}}</ref> Moldova would never hold another military parade until 2001.\n\n==Independence parades==\nThe following parades were held in recent years:\n\n* In 2001, Moldova celebrated the 10th anniversary of independence. It was the first parade since the fall of the USSR and was ordered by President [[Vladimir Voronin]] in early July.<ref>https://www.legis.md/cautare/getResults?doc_id=57381&lang=ro</ref><ref>http://lex.justice.md/index.php?action=view&view=additional&id=287992&lang=1</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Moldova+Independence+Day|title=On August 27, 2001, the first military parade was held in Chisinau to celebrate the first 10 years of the country's independence.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l4BpAAAAMAAJ&q=Moldova+independence+day+parade.&dq=Moldova+independence+day+parade.&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiL_oWE9Z_cAhUY24MKHYJEAy0Q6AEIOjAG|title=Russia & Eurasia Facts & Figures Annual|date=19 August 2018|publisher=Academic International Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* 2011 celebrated the 20th anniversary of independence.<ref>https://www.dw.com/ro/moldova-%C3%AEn-pas-european-de-defilare-la-20-de-ani-de-independen%C5%A3%C4%83/a-15345526</ref> Acting President [[Marian Lupu]], who signed the order for the parade that April<ref>http://ru.interlic.md/2011-04-20/v-kishineve-po-sluchaju-20j-godovcshiny-provozglashenija-nezavisimosti-moldovy-projdet-voennyj-parad-20794.html</ref> delivered the holiday address during the parade. Inspecting the parade was the [[Ministry of Defense (Moldova)|Minister of Defense]] of Moldova [[Vitalie Marinu\u021ba]] while the officer commanding the parade was Brigadier General Vitalie Stoian from the National Army's General Staff.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=835#.WaWth8tOkwg]</ref> Dress rehearsals took place three, seven and ten days before the parade, with the first rehearsal on August being attended by [[Prime Minister of Moldova]] [[Vlad Filat]].<ref>https://regnum.ru/news/1436300.html</ref><ref>https://www.blackseanews.net/read/23266</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/index.php?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=825#.WaN9vctOkwg|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=814#.WaN9wctOkwg|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-08-28}}</ref> It was the first time [[military equipment]] had been brought to the central square sine 1989.<ref>http://www.vedomosti.md/news/Moldova_Prazdnuet_20yu_Godovshchinu_Provozglasheniya_Nezavisimosti</ref> At the head of the parade were the [[flag of Moldova]], as well as the military banners of the Emperor [[Stefan the Great]], which were brought to Chisinau from [[Romania]] as a gesture on their part.<ref>https://point.md/ru/novosti/obschestvo/vladimir-filat-skoro-kazhdij-politicheskij-lider-kazhdij-deputat-kazhdaya-partiya-dolzhni-budut-prodemonstrirovatj-politicheskuyu-zrel</ref> The contingent of veterans of the [[Transnistrian War]] was led by [[Division General]] [[Ion Costa\u0219]], a former [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Moldova)|Minister of Interior]] (1990\u20131992) and Defence (1992).<ref name=\":1\">https://gagauzinfo.md/top1/1389-v-kishineve-proshel-voennyjj-parad-po.html</ref> A new, more western style marching formula was used for the parade<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=699#.WgiVCWOnHEZ|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-11-12}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> as well as new military uniforms were used during the parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=729#.WaN9O8tOkwg|title=Ministry of Defense of Republic of Moldova|website=www.army.md|access-date=2017-08-28}}</ref>\n* 2016 celebrated the [[silver jubilee]] of Moldovan independence. It was the first to use a revised format that was similar to the [[Great Union Day]] Parade in [[Bucharest]]. The following 6 foreign contingents took part in the parade for the first time: [[Odessa Military Academy]] ([[Ukraine]]),{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} the [[Michael the Brave 30th Guards Brigade]] and the [[Asociatia Traditia Militara]] contingent ([[Romania]]), the [[Representative Honor Guard Battalion of the Polish Armed Forces]] ([[Poland]]), the [[Grand Duke Gediminas Staff Battalion]] ([[Lithuania]]), and a 4-man group from the [[Royal Irish Regiment (1992)|Royal Irish Regiment]] ([[United Kingdom]]).{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} Servicemen of the [[Russian Armed Forces]] were also invited to the parade.<ref>https://novostipmr.com/ru/news/16-07-19/rossiyskie-voennye-priglasheny-na-parad-v-chest-25-letiya</ref> More than 2,000 soldiers, as well as veterans of the army marched in the parade. The commander of the parade was the [[Chief of the General Staff (Moldova)|Chief of the General Staff of the Moldovan Armed Forces]], Brigadier General Igor Cutie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.md/?lng=3&action=show&cat=122&obj=3976#.WaNz-MtOkwj|title=The military parade was opened by Parade\u2019s Commander, Brigadier Gen. Igor Cutie, owner of \"Credinta Patriei\" order, holder of \"Meritul Militar\" medal, and participant to the war for the independence and territorial integrity of the Republic of Moldova,}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.kp.md/online/news/2493337/|title=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435 [\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e+\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e]|last=\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|first=\u0422\u041a\u0410\u0427 \u041b\u0438\u0434\u0438\u044f {{!}} \u0421\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439|date=2016-08-28|work=KP.MD - \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|access-date=2017-11-11}}</ref> During the 2016 parade, Moldovan police fired tear gas to disperse anti-government protesters who were participating in the [[2015\u201316 protests in Moldova|2015\u201316 protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/08/27/protests-tear-gas-at-moldova-independence-day-parade.html|title=Protests, tear gas at Moldova independence day parade|date=2016-08-27|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-07-03|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Moldovan Police Clash With Protesters On Independence Day|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/moldova-independence-day/27950971.html|accessdate=2017-07-03}}</ref> Opposition parties previously had called for rallies to disrupt the military parade, launching an \"I'm not afraid\" campaign on social media. Opposition lawyer Anna Ursaki said the following in favor of protests: \"If the authorities have the right to organize parades, to have a feast during the plague, when people are miserable, we have the right to protests\".<ref>https://novostipmr.com/ru/news/16-08-22/v-moldove-oppoziciya-prizvala-mitingami-sorvat-parad-v-chest</ref>\n\n==Parade composition==\nThe parade has the following general composition:<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>https://ria.ru/20110827/423854478.html</ref>\n\n*Officers of the National Army\n*[[Honor Guard Company (Moldova)|Honor Guard Company]]\n*Infantry Troops\n*[[22nd Peacekeeping Battalion (Moldova)|22nd Peacekeeping Battalion]]\n*Paratroopers\n*[[Moldovan Border Police]]\n*Officers of the Ministry of the Interior\n*\u0218tefan cel Mare Police Academy\n*Lyceum of police\n*Special-purpose brigade\n*[[State Protection and Guard Service of Moldova]]\n*Civil Protection and Emergency Situations Service\n*[[Trupele de Carabinieri]]\n*[[Alexandru cel Bun Military Academy]]\n\n===Military bands in attendance===\n[[File:Orchestra preziden\u021bial\u0103.jpeg|thumb|The [[Presidential Orchestra of the Republic of Moldova]]]]\nThe [[military band]]s of the Chisinau Garrison who take part in the parade are composed of:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.publika.md/parada-militara-impresionanta-de-ziua-independentei-moldovei-cine-va-participa-in-premiera_2724211.html|title=Military parade dedicated to the anniversary of 25 years since Moldova's independence will end with the evolution of the orchestra mixed garrison Chisinau, composed of five military orchestras: Presidential Orchestra of the Republic of Moldova, Orchestra Brigade 1st Infantry Motorized \"Moldova\" Balti Orchestra Brigade two motorized infantry \"\u015etefan cel Mare\" in Chisinau Orchestra Motorized Brigade 3rd Infantry \"Dacia\" Cahul Orchestra model Carabineer Troops Department of the Interior Ministry, MIA Border Police Band.|access-date=}}</ref>\n \n* The [[Presidential Orchestra of the Republic of Moldova]]\n* The Band of the [[1st Motorized Infantry Brigade \"Moldova\"|1st Motorized Infantry Brigade]]\n* The Band of the [[2nd Motorized Infantry Brigade \"Stefan Cel Mare\"|2nd Motorized Infantry Brigade]]\n* The Band of the [[3rd Motorized Infantry Brigade \"Dacia\"|3rd Motorized Infantry Brigade]]\n* [[Band of the Department of Carabinier Troops]]\n* [[Central Band of the Moldovan Border Police|Central Band of the Border Police]]\n\n== Photos of the parade ==\n<gallery>\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 08.jpg|\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 07.jpg|\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 10.jpg|\nFile:08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 06.jpg|Ukrainian troops drawn from the [[Odessa Military Academy]] during the 2016 parade.\nFile:25 \u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438 06.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kiev Independence Day Parade]]\n* [[Minsk Independence Day Parade]]\n\n== Videos ==\n* [https://m.youtube.com/watch?list=PL030PgM6el9I_ftCCk-fIW8w407R1slAo&v=ga7mFVlWRag 2001 Chisinau Independence Day Parade.]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4LZAOiNTdUg 2011 Chisinau Independence Day Parade.]\n* [https://m.youtube.com/watch?list=PL030PgM6el9I_ftCCk-fIW8w407R1slAo&params=OAFIAVgB&v=8RphgV0ubiY&mode=NORMAL 2016 Chisinau Independence Day Parade.]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chi\u0219in\u0103u Independence Day Parade}}\n[[Category: